  <mainDescription>An actor &quot;specifies a role played by a user or any other system that interacts with the subject&quot; (&lt;a&#xD;
href=&quot;http://www.uml.org/&quot;>OMG 2007&lt;/a>) or system. An actor may have one or more roles, and can be equated to the external&#xD;
people or systems that interact with the system under study. Business Actors are high-level conceptualizations of the&#xD;
Actors with the system; further analysis is required to fully understand and define required actors. Note that actors are&#xD;
&lt;b>&lt;i>not&lt;/i>&lt;/b> individuals nor are they necessarily equivalent to job titles instead, they describe the behavior in the&#xD;
enterprise and the responsibilities of the associated &quot;user&quot;. An employee of the enterprise is typically multiple actors&#xD;
(e.g. employee, manager, analyst, etc.) and therefore has many different roles (e.g. employee-HR, budgeter, manager-HR,&#xD;
expense claimer, etc.). The mapping from individuals to actors and roles is essentially performed by managers within the&#xD;
enterprise when defining and staffing the positions within their organization. Also see the definition of &lt;em>&lt;a&#xD;
class=&quot;elementLink&quot; href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/termdefinitions/uam_business_role_C84248F6.html&quot;&#xD;
guid=&quot;_HAuMMMIqEeKSedlRPHdUIQ&quot;>Business Role&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em>and &lt;em>&lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
href=&quot;./../../../UAM/guidances/termdefinitions/uam_role_F41637E3.html&quot; guid=&quot;_4cjbMOPNEdy7f9KmjDtwsA&quot;>Role&lt;/a>&lt;/em>.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br /></mainDescription>
